(255563, 8496, 255479, 'Avais', 3335, '', 1331994851, '[QUOTE=Chauhdary;255479].177, .20, .22, .25, .357 (9mm), 308, .45, .457, .50\nMost common ones being .177 and .22, followed by .25 and then .20. Big bore airguns are a different story altogether, they''re PCP (multi-shot airguns, also available in smaller cals) used for taking down big game.\n\n.177 for target shooting/competitive shooting, .22 for hunting, .20 as a 50/50 between the previously mentioned 2 calibers... and .25 is the most powerful among these small-bores but a more rainbow-like trajectory. .177 has the flattest trajectory, while the bigger the caliber - the more ft/lbs of energy transferred into the quarry.\n\nJust an intro to big-bores;\n[URL]http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KMiDaCdfVh8[/URL][/QUOTE]\nThanks Ch., brother for the info. I did not knew about this.', 1, 0, '119.154.115.238', 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'on_nl2br', 0, 0),
