(258329, 8187, 244696, 'TRX', 7332, '', 1333182920, 'When the US Army adopted the .45-70 cartridge in 1873 it required that the cartridges be reloadable.  Fired cases were shipped back to the arsenal for reloading, as the Army had a much smaller budget back in those days. Later, when the Tsar''s armorers had their new Mosin-Nagant rifles and ammunition produced in the USA, they also required their cases be reloadable.  The Tsar also bought a lot of Winchester lever-action rifles chambered in 7.62x54R for his cavalry. I mention these because while it''s widely known American civilians have historically reloaded ammunition, it''s not as widely known that there were sometimes military requirements as well.', 1, 0, '76.125.99.223', 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'on_nl2br', 0, 0),
